Product Name: Split & Ship (Gainsight Edition)
1. User Experience (UX) Flow
The goal is "Zero Confusion." A user seeing a "File Too Large" error in Gainsight should be able to fix it here in under 30 seconds.

Step 1: The "Drop Zone" (Landing)
Action: Large, clean drag-and-drop area.

Visual Cue: Text saying "Drop your CSV here (Up to 10GB+ supported)".

Immediate Feedback: As soon as the file drops, show the file name, total size (e.g., "2.1 GB"), and total row count (calculated via a quick stream scan).

Step 2: Configuration (The "Easy Button")
Give users two distinct paths:

Path A: "Gainsight Safe Mode" (Recommended)

One-Click Button: Automatically sets the split size to 200 MB (Gainsight's safe zone) and ensures the filename works with Gainsight's wildcard match.

Why: Removes the guesswork for the user.

Path B: Custom Mode

Input Fields: Allow splitting by Max File Size (MB) OR Max Rows.

Naming: Custom prefix field (e.g., usage_data_part_).

Step 3: Processing & Visualization
Visual: A progress bar showing "Processing Part 1... Part 2...".

Crucial UX Detail: Don't freeze the browser. Use a "Web Worker" (background thread) so the user can still scroll or cancel while it processes.

Step 4: The Output
Action: Single button: "Download All as ZIP".

Bonus: Display the specific "Wildcard Pattern" the user needs to type into Gainsight (e.g., "In Gainsight S3 settings, use prefix: upload_part_").

2. Technical Architecture (For Developers)
To build this, you need a stack that handles large files without crashing the browser tab (OOM - Out of Memory errors).

Tech Stack: React (or Vue/Svelte) + Web Workers.

Key Library: JSZip (for bundling results).

The Logic (The "Slice & Seek" Method):

Do NOT load the whole file into RAM.

Do NOT read line-by-line (too slow for 2GB).

The Algorithm:

Read Header: Extract the first line (Bytes 0 to N) to keep for every file.

Chunking: Calculate the byte offset for the target size (e.g., 200MB).

Alignment: Jump to that 200MB mark, then read forward byte-by-byte to find the nearest \n (newline character).

Slice: Cut the file at that exact newline using File.slice(start, end).

Repeat: Start the next chunk from that newline.

Save: Stream these slices directly into a ZIP file.

